ical categories and to explore the historical dimension of those categories. Drawing in particular on Russian Formalism, he develops a theory of the dynamics of literary change and of the historical pressures that shape the literary system. He tests and extends his categories through readings of texts by Petronius, Hölderlin, DeLillo, Dickens, Frank Hardy, and others. The final chapter, a reading of Derrida and Foucault, poses the question of the possibility of setting limits to reading and the power of limits to determine literary history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCritique marxiste. 0aCrítica. 0aDiscours littéraire. 0aDiscourse analysis, Literary. 0aLiteratur, Rhetorik, Literaturwissenschaft. 0aMarxist criticism. 4aDiscourse analysis, Literary. 4aLITERARY CRITICISM / General. 4aLITERARY CRITICISM / Russian & Former Soviet Union. 4aMarxist criticism. 4aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Communism, Post-Communism & Socialism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488oZDB-23-HCO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Literature eBook Packagez9783110353501oZDB-23-HLI08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z97831104422120 cprintz978067433280540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067433281240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674332812423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674332812.jpg  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-HCO  aZDB-23-